ury is a small town where I live. It has a population of around 85,000 people. Some of the buildings people live in are 500 years old, and there are lots of houses built before the 1950\'s. These are really hard to make more energy efficient. But, lots of new houses are being built and these should be easier to design differently and better.\r\n\r\nGiven the context of mixed housing stock, solutions might need to be adaptable to the type of house: new build, newer brick buildings, and older stone or timber framed buildings.\r\n\r\nWhy is this important? Apart from the obvious reason of climate change, we are getting hotter summers and warmer winters. Traditionally houses are built to protect from cold not deal with heat. We need to think more about how new houses can be better at dealing with hotter temperatures without uses lots of energy (remember climate change).                                ','My design will address how new build houses can maintain a comfortable temperature during the summer months, even when the outside temperature can be over 30 degrees. \r\n\r\nThe design solutions will need to be simple to implement and not have a high running costs. They must also not create a price increase in the cost of the house.\r\n\r\nThe solution will also need to be aware of the need for houses to have good insulation in the winter months to retain warmth and reduce the costs of artifical heating.\r\n\r\nWhich of Nature\'s Unifying Patterns will be most applicable?\r\n1. Nature is locally atuned and responsive - my design needs to adapt to local conditions.\r\n2. Nature uses shape to determine functionality - by using shape/form to achieve my results I can reduce the need for ongoing costs.\r\n\r\n','2022-09-30 15:27:05',4,'2022-09-30 15:27:05',4,NULL,NULL),(242,79,37,'  context',NULL,'2022-10-03 09:06:46',1,'2022-10-03 09:06:46',1,NULL,NULL),(243,79,37,'  context ',NULL,'2022-10-03 09:31:15',1,'2022-10-03 09:31:15',1,NULL,NULL),(244,41,8,'Shrewsbury is a small town where I live. It has a population of around 85,000 people. Some of the buildings people live in are 500 years old, and there are lots of houses built before the 1950\'s. These are really hard to make more energy efficient. But, lots of new houses are being built and these should be easier to design differently and better.\r\n\r\nGiven the context of mixed housing stock, solutions might need to be adaptable to the type of house: new build, newer brick buildings, and older stone or timber framed buildings.\r\n\r\nWhy is this important? Apart from the obvious reason of climate change, we are getting hotter summers and warmer winters. Traditionally houses are built to protect from cold not deal with heat. We need to think more about how new houses can be better at dealing with hotter temperatures without uses lots of energy (remember climate change).                                 ',NULL,'2022-10-04 10:43:48',4,'2022-10-04 10:43:48',4,NULL,NULL),(245,42,98,'       ',NULL,'2022-10-10 10:24:31',9,'2022-10-10 10:24:31',9,NULL,NULL),(246,42,98,'        ',NULL,'2022-10-10 10:30:13',9,'2022-10-10 10:30:13',9,NULL,NULL),(247,42,98,'         ',NULL,'2022-10-10 10:35:25',9,'2022-10-10 10:35:25',9,NULL,NULL),(248,91,100,' A víz a mindennapjaink fontos része és jól kell vele gazdálkodjunk. Nagy mennyiségű vizet fogyasztunk: ivóvíznek, háztartásban, mezőgazdaságban és az iparban. Az esővíz nagy része kárba vész, bár nagyon sok helyen felhasználható lenne. Feltevődik a kérdés, hogy hogyan lehet úgy összegyűjteni az esővizet hogy az minél több helyen felhasználható legyen. A legkézenfekvőbb megoldás a háztető csatornarendszerében összegyűlt esővizet tárolni és felhasználni.  ',NULL,'2022-10-16 07:49:53',12,'2022-10-16 07:49:53',12,NULL,NULL),(249,134,134,'We live in Johannesburg (Joburg), South Africa. The population of Joburg is 6 million people. Lots of people come to Joburg from other provinces and neighbouring countries to find jobs. This results in a large amount of people not having money for accommodation and so they build makeshift housing out of materials such as corrugated iron etc in areas without proper infrastructure such as roads, running water, sewerage and electricity. \r\nJoburg has summer rainfall (average temperature 26 degrees celsius) and dry, cold winters (average temperature 17 degrees celsius). Highs in summer can reach 36 degrees celsius and in winter the lows can drop to -3 degrees celsius.\r\nThe informal/squatter settlements are not formally planned and are occupied illegally and therefore have problems such as crime, litter/pollution, lack of health facilities, lack of clean water, health issues (physical and mental), poor road access, no electricity, limited access to fresh fruit and vegetables. They are often in areas that are not ideal for housing. \r\nIf our house design works and we designed it in collaboration with the communities, listening to their wants and needs, then  this solution could help the community members by creating employment and cash flow,  giving people skills which could lead to more jobs and creating housing that keeps people healthy and has a minimal impact on the environment.  ','','2022-11-08 11:26:31',200,'2022-11-08 11:26:31',200,NULL,NULL),(250,79,37,'  context  ','','2022-12-07 11:43:49',225,'2022-12-07 11:43:49',225,NULL,NULL),(251,79,37,'  context   ','','2022-12-07 16:25:42',225,'2022-12-07 16:25:42',225,NULL,NULL),(252,79,37,'asdasdasdasd','','2022-12-08 10:54:54',225,'2022-12-08 10:54:54',225,NULL,NULL);
